	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Export earnings rise in Uganda, but fishermen lose</h1>

			
			<h4>
												31 March 2006
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p> A spot assessment by a delegation of experts from the East African Community has shown that fish prices have shot up by 60% around Lake Victoria, according to the newspaper <i>New Vision</i> (Kampala) on March 10th 2006. ‘An average size tilapia that used to cost Sh1,200 is now going for Sh2,600 and more than Sh5,200 in some hotels,’ said a fisherman. This price rise was attributed to poor catches due to the fall in Lake Victoria's water levels.</p><p> The same newspaper later reported on a study entitled ‘Trade liberalisation and its effects on poverty, food security and livelihoods at local level in Uganda’. This showed that, despite a continuous increase in fish export earnings, benefits from the trade still elude most of the local fishing communities. The inequality in sharing benefits from expanded fish exports is partly the result of a liberalisation, in which the government has only a limited role in regulating the players. It has not been possible for small-scale fishers to make any significant investments in order to boost their activities, since they lack the finance, and the government is not willing to provide the funds. The situation has been worsened by the inability of most fishers to secure loans from banks due to lack of any collateral as security, as well as the unaffordable interest rates on the loans.</p><p>
 The report recommended that local communities should be given technical and financial assistance to invest in fish harvesting and processing, in particular so as to meet EU standards. The report also recommended financial support in form of tailor-made loans to empower the fishers.<br /> </p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p> Article in <i>New Vision</i> (Kampala) </p><p>

<a href="http://www.newvision.co.ug/D/8/220/488659" target="_self">http://www.newvision.co.ug/D/8/220/488659</a> <br /> Article in <i>New Vision</i> (Kampala)</p><p>

<a href="http://newvision.co.ug/D/8/220/486403" target="_self">http://newvision.co.ug/D/8/220/486403</a> <br /> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> Of interest for all ACP countries, and highlighted by the Uganda situation, is the discussion about the role of the state, and its strengths and weaknesses, in regulating the players in the fisheries sector. In the past, a lack of regulation has often been observed in the sector, either due to a lack of means, or to the fact that a lack of regulations was sometimes perceived as an easy way to attract quick foreign investment. As in the case of Lake Victoria, a lack of regulation has led to an impoverishment both of the resources and local populations depending on these resources.</p><p> If the need to regulate the fishing sector is well established today, the importance of financial support in implementing such regulations is often overlooked, and the role of the state in providing or facilitating this financial support is not well defined.</p><p> In a context of liberalisation, there is an urgent need for strong state intervention to regulate fisheries, including through appropriate financial support, for the long-term benefit of the populations who depend on them for their food and livelihoods.</p>
		</div>
		
